Crime Boss Putin
Moscow — German, French, and Swedish medical experts have reached a consensus that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Putin and also the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
It is fortunate that Russia and Germany's relationship did not deteriorate, as Navalny survived.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel announced that Navalny is "a victim of persecution due to freedom of speech."
In her view, the incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can, and must, respond.
She emphasized that the entire world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation results prove that the Russian government is the mastermind behind the incident, the European Commission will impose another round of sanctions.
No matter what, according to the Chemical Weapons Convention, poisoning is a prohibited act.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to target its political opponents.
In 2018, Russian former double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding Navalny's case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov firmly stated, "There is no evidence to accuse the Russian government."
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service Director Sergei Naryshkin even claimed it was an act by Western intelligence agencies, thereby damaging the credibility of the Russian government.
Naryshkin's claim is clearly unreasonable, but he also pointed out a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
It is simply indefensible to poison a prominent political opponent just before an upcoming election, especially using a nerve agent developed by the former Soviet Union.
Especially in the context of protests by Belarusian citizens against the August elections, this timing is even more intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny incident was especially confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If, as Germany claims, it was indeed the Russian government that carried it out, this murder was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of international politics (the number one rebel figure in the movie *Star Wars*), intervening in the U.S. election, inciting street protests in France, enticing Brexit in the UK, and supporting Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB officer, he was shrewd, visionary, and cunning.
Then why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why could Navalny flee to Germany, and why was he quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project to Germany faces cancellation.
This murder clearly backfired.
In fact, this has further fueled public opposition to the misconduct of the Russian authorities.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, the accusation against Western intelligence agencies is even more excessive.
If such accusations are true, German and Swedish scientists would not have revealed the fact that the nerve agent Novichok was used.
More likely, it stems from a conspiracy orchestrated by Putin's political inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to shut up before the election, or perhaps it was the trouble caused by his anti-corruption investigations.
In Russia, you can buy a variety of products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, though loyal, are very foolish, and they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, with only a small number of participants knowing the truth.
Other failed poisoning operations share similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Murza was the coordinator of the public investigation committee of Khodorkovsky.
The poisoning of Peter Verkhivsky, the publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on judicial overreach in Russia.
Further back to 2006, the poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko, a former KGB officer who frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
As with the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper *Novaya Gazeta*, was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan, although she survived, she was later shot dead in the elevator of her apartment two years later.
As Putin said, her death dealt a significant blow to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
No matter whether Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allowed such crimes to take place. Such a system is both ineffective and useless, and it is a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death was the desired outcome of the Kremlin, and pleasing the master Putin was the ultimate goal of the henchmen.
Loyalty is the only goal within Putin's inner circle.
Even if the poisoning failed, they would not face punishment.
Because they did it for the benefit of the president.
Those seeking evidence of the poisoning may end up disappointed.
No matter what, the Kremlin is the real culprit.
Western countries must clearly state their position, even if their own economy is affected, and take sanctions against Russia.
Putin created a system centered around himself.
All the blame for what happened in Russia falls on himself.
